This is shortly for the LIN-bus that connects:
- N154 HVAC Control unit (N154)
- S98/1, front AC control panel
- S98/2, rear AC control panel
- A49/5, Remote control control unit (Code HY1)
- N33/3, warm water stationary heater

I did connect my LIN-sniffer (See other repo) via the front AC control panel using an 3-pin MQS-adapter from aliexpress. Look for "TE/AMP 2-929169-1 A 3 Pin"

So far I've just started, here are the PID's that are found:
0x0D 0x20 0x3F 0x49 0x4C 0x5E 0x76 0x78 0x8B 0x8E 0xCF 0xDD
And a new:
0x0D 0x20 0x3F 0x49 0x4C 0x50 0x5E 0x76 0x78 0x8B 0x8E 0xCF 0xDD
Mapping will start someday.
The up/down-buttons work in a funny way.
They have three states, heres one example, this varies from button to button:
- button up:         00001101
- Button middle:     00001011
- button down:       00001001
- 0x0D: Could be buttons or a master feedback
        byte 0:
        // Standard bit order: 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 0
        // Bit 7: btn, rear temperature (up/down)
        // Bit 6: btn, rear temperature (up/down)
        // Bit 5: btn, rear temperature (up/down)
        // Bit 4: btn, rear temperature (up/down)
        byte 3:
        // Standard bit order: 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 0
        // Bit 7: btn, rear fan (up/down)
        // Bit 6: btn, rear fan (up/down)
        // Bit 5: btn, rear fan (up/down)
        // Bit 4: btn, rear fan (up/down)
- 0x20: Unknown
- 0x3F: Unknown
- 0x49: Unknown
        byte 0:
        // Standard bit order: 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 0
        // Bit 3: btn, Aux heater
- 0x4C: Here be some buttons. Maybe
        byte 0:
        // Standard bit order: 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 0
        // Bit 5: btn, menu
        // Bit 0: btn, auto
        byte 1:
        // Standard bit order: 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 0
        // Bit 7: btn, right direction (up/down)
        // Bit 6: btn, right direction (up/down)
        // Bit 5: btn, right direction (up/down)
        // Bit 4: btn, right direction (up/down)
        byte 2:
        // Standard bit order: 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 0
        // Bit 3: btn, fan (up/down)
        // Bit 2: btn, fan (up/down)
        // Bit 1: btn, fan (up/down
        // Bit 0: btn, fan (up/down)
        byte 3:
        // Standard bit order: 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 0
        // Bit 3: btn, left temp (up/down)
        // Bit 2: btn, left temp (up/down)
        // Bit 1: btn, left temp (up/down
        // Bit 0: btn, left temp (up/down)
        byte 4:
        // Standard bit order: 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 0
        // Bit 3: btn, right temp (up/down)
        // Bit 2: btn, right temp (up/down)
        // Bit 1: btn, right temp (up/down
        // Bit 0: btn, right temp (up/down)
        byte 5:
        // Standard bit order: 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 0
        // Bit 7: btn, left direction (up/down)
        // Bit 6: btn, left direction (up/down)
        // Bit 5: btn, left direction (up/down)
        // Bit 4: btn, left direction (up/down)
- 0x50: Unknown
- 0x5E: Unknown
- 0x76: Aux heater?
        // Byte 0, start request, follows LED (device on, not really request)
        // byte 1, can be blower? .> not really. Fluctuates while device off. -> More certain that it is blower
        // Byte 2, Y141?? -> most probable
        // Byte 3, flame sensor temp? offset -141? maybe not -> reacts to car start, but not stop -> or is temp sensor?
        // byte 4, stays FF
        // byte 5-7, stays 
- 0x78: aux heater?
        // Byte 0, Coolant temp. offset -40
        // Byte 1, operating condition
                0x00 off
                0x04 Half load
                0x07 full load
        // Byte 2, fuel pump? (0-9Hz) OR Y141 OR heat output *OR blower*
        // byte 3, follows start request 
        // byte 4, follows start request
        // byte 5-6 stays FF
        // byte 7 follows start request
        // byte 3, 4, 7 follow 0x76 byte 0 quite well

- 0xDD: Aux heater?
        // byte 0, stary high, but not FF
        // byte 1, follows voltage OR engine start -> not engine start. Coolant temp does not increase at change, but reacts to voltage.
        // Byte 2, flame sensor? OR Load target/state OR blower - FOLLOWS byte 1 -> byte 1 and 2 voltage? neither follows voltage fluctuation. -> not engine start. Coolant temp does not increase at change, but reacts to voltage.
        // Byte 3, combustion air blower speed -> NOT. Follows door unlock and from there also voltage spikes. 2-byte voltage with byte2? -> not engine start. Coolant temp does not increase at change, but reacts to voltage. -> not door lock
        // byte 4, also follows door unlock and voltage drops -> not engine start, not door lock. Coolant temp does not increase at change, but reacts to voltage.
        // byte 5, also follows door unlock and voltage drops -> not engine start, not door lock. Coolant temp does not increase at change, but reacts to voltage.
        // byte 6-7 stays mostly FF
- 0x8B: Some leds. 
        byte 0:
        // Standard bit order: 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 0
        // Bit 5: LED, rest
        // Bit 4: LED, interior circulation on
        byte 1: follows fan speed?
        byte 5:
        // Standard bit order: 7 6 5 4 3 2 1 0
        // Bit 7: Auto Off (1) / Auto On (0)
        // Bit 5: Rear Window Heater
        // Bit 4: Always 1 (Base state)
        // Bit 2: Aux Heat Timer
        // Bit 1: Aux Heat Ventilation
        // Bit 0: Aux Heat On 
- 0x8E: Some buttons
- 0xCF: Rear display
- 0xDD: Unknown
